<seg id=1> U.S. Admits Air Raids Killed Several Hundred Iraqi Civilians, British Reporter Says Nonmilitary Targets Bombed </seg>
</hl>
<p>
<seg id=2> According to Xinhua News Agency, February 13, Telegram:  The U.S. White House admitted on the 13th that the multinational airforce, when conducting an air raid on the Iraqi capital Baghdad, caused the death of several hundred Iraqi civilians, but insisted that the targets struck by multinational forces were military targets.  </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id=3> Whitehouse Spokesperson Fitzwater said that the U.S. government felt that "this was indeed a tragic outcome." </seg>
<seg id=4> However, he accused Iraqi President Saddam [Hussein] of arranging for civilians to be in military facilities and placing them in danger. </seg>
<seg id=5> He said that the U.S. believed that the target struck was an Iraqi military command and control center. </seg>
<seg id=6> "This facility, "had been painted and camouflaged to escape surveillance, but the evidence demonstrates that this was a military target." </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id=7> According to Xinhua News Agency, February 13, Telegram:  A BBC reporter stationed in the Iraqi capital of Baghdad named Bowen verified that there was no indication that an air-raid shelter in Baghdad destroyed by U.S. bombers was an Iraqi military bunker. </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id=8> These statements by Bowen on BBC television news repudiate assertions made by U.S. officials that the air-raid shelter was a camouflaged military bunker. </seg>
<seg id=9> Bowen had been on-site and visited the bombed air-raid shelter where about 400 civilians lost their lives. </seg>
</p>
